  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 형설(螢雪) : '
    value: 낭형(囊螢)과 조설(照雪)을 합칭한 말임. 《진서(晉書)》 거륜전(車胤傳)에 “윤(胤)이 학(學)에 넓고 통한 것이 많은데, 집이 가난하여 노상 기름을 구득할 수 없으므로, 여름이면 주머니를 만들어 반딧불 수십 마리를 넣어서 책에 비추어 보며 밤을 지샜다.” 하였고, 또 옛 사람이 겨울 밤이면 눈 위에서 글을 본 사람도 있었다. 그래서 부지런히 공부 한다는 뜻으로 쓰인다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 연벽(聯璧) : '
    value: 두 구슬이 서로 연했단 말로, 둘이 똑같이 아름답다는 표현이다. 진서(晉書) 하후담전(夏侯湛傳)에, “담(湛)은 풍채가 아름다우며 반악(潘岳)과 더불어 사이가 좋아서 나가면 수레를 함께 타고, 앉으면 자리를 같이하니 서울 사람들이 연벽(聯璧)이라 칭하였다.” 하였다. 후에 와서는 형제(兄弟)가 동방(同榜)으로 과거한 데 쓰기도 한다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 부신(負薪) : '
    value: 자기 병을 말하는 겸사(謙辭)이다. 《예기(禮記)》 곡례(曲禮)에, 임금이 선비로 하여금 활을 쏘게 할 적에, 만약 능하지 못하면 병을 칭하여 사양하는 말이, “저는 섶나무를 짊어진 여독이 있습니다[某有負薪之憂].” 하였고, 그 주에, “부(負)는 짊어진단 말이요, 신(薪)은 나무, 우(憂)는 노고란 말이다. 이를테면 몸이 나무를 짊어진 여독이 있어서 활을 이겨 쏠 수가 없다는 것이며, 병을 말하지 않고 나무를 짊어졌다고 한 것은, 만약 병을 바로 말하면 오만한 것같으므로 병의 소유래(所由來)만 아뢰는 것이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 장진(張陳) : '
    value: 형제간의 우애를 말한 것이다. 진(陳)은 진원방(陳元方)ㆍ계방(季方) 형제를 말한 것이고, 장(張)은 장공예(張公藝)의 구세동거(九世同居)를 말한 것인지 미상이다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 치란(治亂)의 명령 : '
    value: 치명(治命)은 합리적(合理的)인 유명(遺命)이요, 난명(亂命)은 죽게 되어 정신이 착란할 때의 유명이다. 위(魏)나라의 무자(武子)가 병이 들어 그의 아들 과(顆)에게 명령하기를, “내가 죽으면 내 첩들을 시집보내라.” 하더니, 병이 위독하여서는, “반드시 순장(殉葬)을 해 달라.” 하였다. 무자가 죽자, 과는 시집보내며 하는 말이, “병이 심하면 정신이 착란한 것이니, 나는 정신이 온전할 때의 치명(治命)을 따르겠다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 황량(黃梁) : '
    value: 황량몽(黃梁夢)을 말한 것인데, 한단몽(邯鄲夢)이라고도 함. 《열선전(列仙傳)》에, “당(唐)나라의 노생(盧生)이 주막에서 여옹(呂翁)에게서 베개를 얻었다. 그 때에 주막집 주인이 노란 조[黃梁]를 찧고 있는데, 베개를 베니 잠이 들어서 꿈속에서 베개 속으로 들어가 영화롭게 살다가 18세로 죽는 꿈을 꾸었다. 꿈을 깨고 보니 노란 조가 아직도 익지 아니하였기로, ‘이것이 꿈이란 말인가’ 하니, 옹은 웃으면서, ‘인간 세상 일도 역시 이와 같다.’하였다.” 한다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 哀 : '
    value: 衷
  - key: '[주-D002] 偣 : '
    value: 暗
english:
  title: Lamentation for Zhong Yun
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Oh brother, have you truly abandoned me and departed forever? I cannot yet accept that you are gone—surely this grief has driven me to madness. Mother still dwells in the hall, my sisters are well, you were occupied with duty, and I remained at your side. How could you alone leave this place? Where is there more precious than home? How have you cast aside the love of bone and blood like worn-out shoes?

    Your beloved weeps, the servants cry out, your nephews shed tears of blood, and kinfolk come to mourn—yet you hear nothing. You lie prostrate and do not rise. Has your weariness with this world's clamor reached such extremity? Was it a dream? Yesterday you spoke with joy, yesterday you laughed. In a single day, you neither spoke nor smiled, but lay withered and senseless. Words could not convey your meaning, illness could not explain its symptoms, medicine could not touch your tongue, and fire could not reach your pain. Thus you leave me with boundless sorrow.

    Heaven! Heaven! This anguish threatens to shatter me. Below live countless people—what displeasure has Heaven shown you? Yan Hui's life was short, Yuan Si endured endless poverty. Jiang Shi sent away his wife, Meng Dongye had no son. What human suffering exceeds this?

    Oh brother, do you know of my suffering, or are you unaware? In that dim and silent place, I know of your death, but do you know that I yet live? Oh, this agony! If death brings oblivion, so be it. But if your spirit remains as luminous as always, surely you understand my heart. Since you perceive it, why do you not come to me and make this known?

    I am nine years your junior. When you had mastered learning, I was still a child. Your filial piety and brotherly love sprang from your very nature. Your heart ever yearned to follow the ancients. Seeing our poverty and parents' age, you sighed at time's passage and warned me of indolence. On every festival, you yourself prepared food for our parents, content only when they had tasted it. In all matters, you obeyed their wishes without deviation. I too learned from you, and gradually understood that this is the way to serve one's parents.

    In the year Gyeongja, we both failed the examination together. Unable to gain office, we turned our eyes from the capital and resolved to fish and farm in the river country, sustaining ourselves by our own labor. Thus we bore our parents back across the mountains southward. Above, we grieved at their decline; below, we worried for our own sustenance. By lamplight in travelers' lodges, amid snow on mountain passes, sitting together we would often weep. Upon reaching our home village, the elders competed to welcome us. At festivals, we shared wine and gathered with neighbors, singing songs that helped us endure the year and forget our sorrows. Yet when we tried to make this simple life our means of serving them, I felt shame at my idleness.

    Studying hard in the mountain lodge, I yet felt my learning insufficient, so I traveled to seek Master Jeom-biljae's door. After several months of instruction, I finally found my way. From that time forward, we moved as one, never separated for a day. Though we were called brothers by heaven's bond, we were truly intimate companions. Wherever we went, we honed each other through poetry and ritual.

    But now all is ended. You cared not for gain or loss, and gazed upon the world with sighs—now from what distance do you observe the petty deeds of dusty men?

    When mother fell ill and feared for my youth, she entrusted me to you. You promised to shield me from hunger and cold. When I traveled to study, mother's meager gifts often could not cover me, and you would remove your own robe to warm my skin. Now as I approach life's twilight, ignorant of livelihood's ways, where shall I turn? Our elder brother rarely followed convention in his youth, yet mother loved your pure integrity, saying, "When I die, I shall surely receive your offerings." How could she know that today she would prepare sacrifice to summon your departed soul?

    When I first took a wife and brought her from Chungcheong, you came to rejoice in my good fortune and embraced the sorrow of parting. We talked through the night, our legs entwined, until the fifth watch crow. You entreated mother to give me fine fields and reliable servants, while you took poor soil and foolish slaves for yourself.

    That winter of Imjin, we studied together by firefly and snow. When you alone was chosen first in the great examination, I forgot my own rejection and rejoiced in your ascent. Your fame rose in a single day to reach the palace itself. You were received in white robes, given imperial broth with the king's own hands. The three of us brothers became like connected pearls, each taking first rank, and what minister or marquis did not honor you?

    Your body had long been afflicted with the burden of fatigue, yet the imperial summons waited for no carriage. Your spirit grew weary as you returned to your home. The king's concern ran deep; physicians came at midnight, and royal words were sent inquiring of your illness and sending medicine. Even we humble folk were startled. Before the lamp, our tears stained our robes.

    Soon after, our father passed. I mourned for three years until my flesh wasted from my bones. Your illness then took hold. When the mourning period ended, you were appointed to office three times in succession. That year Byunggo, I too gained my degree. The three brothers were compared to three pearls. Though the position of Assistant Minister of War was called a high appointment, you did not esteem it for office-seeking, but requested a county, hoping to serve mother better.

    Yet you were banished for negligence. Untroubled, you wandered forests and streams. I too abandoned my post to follow. In misty rain by the stream we cast nets for fish, on flowering spring hills we flew hawks to hunt pheasant. By these means we sustained our parents, and all was possible. When the valley hall was completed and pines and bamboo had grown, we lived in ease and leisure. Yet mother's wish was not that we remain idle, so when appointment came, we could not refuse.

    Your ambition was vast—you would not lag behind others. Learning that the Chief Justice's position had passed you by, you wearied yourself with documents and endless proclamations. Though you stayed but briefly, you returned to bring honor to our aging mother. Yet how were we to know that your very life was melting away like lamp oil, and that the world would continue demanding you add more fuel to the flame?

    Heaven? Spirits? What fault did my brother commit to deserve such cruel punishment? You would leave home idly, arrive late at court. As the sun rose, you would simply return home and sleep, calling out "again, again" three times. Heaven? Spirits? What debt does my brother owe to warrant such poisonous affliction?

    All about the world, many live long lives in ease and plenty. But you—pure and uncontending, wanting nothing from things—should have lived freely, yet instead you labored ten years as a minor official, and exhausted thirty-eight years of mortal life, leaving me unable to share one blanket's warmth with you forever.

    Was it a dream? At first I thought the world's sudden deaths sometimes revive, so even days after, I harbored hope. But now your form lies in one wooden box. I call and you do not hear. You call and I do not hear. In this world we are forever parted. In the next world, whether we shall meet again is unknowable. Thus heaven and earth stretch endless, and the universe is only vast emptiness.

    Last month I sent mother a letter saying all was well, promising to return in the tenth month. Our elder brother attends her; surely the news has comforted her. We would have worn bright silks and brought her joy—how could I have known this day would bring such wailing in this place?

    Had I known, would I not have stayed to care for mother, for you and me together, that we might not reach a state where living and dying, joy and sorrow, remain forever unknown to each other? These days I am like one mad, like one empty-minded. All the ten thousand affairs of humanity seem meaningless.

    I shall receive your bones and return to bury them in our family grave. I shall seek office no more and pass my remaining days thus. Yet I fear: will mother, waiting at the gate for her wandering son to return, suddenly see a hearse and fall into madness? Might my own shock bring disaster? Would your lifelong filial devotion then be marked by your son's unfilial end? If you know of this, surely you cannot close your eyes in peace.

    Uncle Li urges me to bury you in the family grave at Yongin. I have thought on this and find it reasonable. The son of Ji Zi died in Qi and was buried in Yingbo, yet it was said: "Bone and flesh return to earth, but spirit and breath go where they will." Though your remains rest there, your spirit will surely return to our homeland and follow with the ancestors. Would this not bring you peace? Yet I cannot decide for you. I only pray that your bright spirit, appearing in my dreams, will make this known to me. And I pray that if your wandering soul comes to dreams, let it come to mine alone and spare our mother further sleepless nights of weeping.

    Oh, we once shared a bed in our early days, and I thought even the devoted brothers of old could not surpass us. But duty bound me, and we established separate households. Amid the red dust of the world's affairs, days slipped away. Though in the same city, we met but rarely each month. Only days ago we wept together at father's memorial in my home. You wailed with deep sorrow, I grieved intensely. Our faces grew dark as we parted, our hearts' communion incomplete. Yet your complexion seemed full, your spirit undiminished—I thought you free of serious illness. Five days passed without meeting, and then eternal parting.

    Had I known, would I have spent even one night apart from you? Our elder brother has but one son to carry on, while I have no heir. This is the extreme of human sorrow. When I gaze at heaven, it seems infinitely distant. You had a concubine whose commands we never heard, yet perhaps she carries new life. Should it be born and thrive, then you would not be without continuation. If not, then she should be joined to father's tomb, or we should choose from among our cousins' sons to establish your heir. This rests with mother and our elder brother's judgment.

    Oh, this sorrow! I shall arrange your affairs so no Buddhist temple profits from your passing. I shall care for your widow so she wants for nothing. As long as I remain in this world, you need not worry.

    Oh, humanity's upper span is one hundred years, yet most do not reach sixty or seventy. I am but twenty-nine—how many springs and autumns remain to me? The millet in the dream has not yet ripened, yet one lifetime passes in idleness. Heaven and earth have their end, but grass and trees know no sorrow.

    In middle age your nature grew confused. You took to wine and indulgence, and mother grew disappointed. I often recited the poem sent by Jia Tong to Cai, and reproached you earnestly. Do you remember? My warning against wine was to have you abandon that which harms life, to extend your years a few spans more, until our aged mother passed—then you too might follow. How could I have known this sorrow would only deepen today?

    Now when I would offer you a cup, I cannot. And at these words, my sorrow threatens to break me entirely.
  footnotes:
    - 'Firefly and Snow (形設): An allusion to diligent study despite poverty—studying by firefly light in summer and snow light in winter'
    - 'Connected Pearls (聯璧): A metaphor for two brothers of equal excellence both succeeding in the examinations together'
    - 'The Burden of Fatigue (負薪): A modest self-reference to illness, from ritual propriety''s euphemistic language'
    - 'The Millet Dream (黃梁): Allusion to the famous tale of how human life''s span is like an instant—a dream before millet even finishes cooking'
